00:42:37,321 --> 00:42:38,583
I know.

512
00:42:44,562 --> 00:42:47,588
I need you to be a proper bridesmaid.

513
00:42:48,399 --> 00:42:51,163
I need you to be very, very nice to Carl.

514
00:42:52,570 --> 00:42:54,470
Can you do that for me?

515
00:42:54,538 --> 00:42:58,872
Is that what you really and truly
want me to do?

516
00:43:00,844 --> 00:43:04,507
He's a good man
and he'll be a wonderful husband.

517
00:43:06,684 --> 00:43:09,346
Now it's time to hit the deck, dear...

518
00:43:11,889 --> 00:43:13,049
Good morning, Ann.

519
00:43:13,123 --> 00:43:14,283
Good morning.

520
00:43:17,061 --> 00:43:20,394
Well, everything seemed
like a good idea at the time.

521
00:43:20,664 --> 00:43:23,326
One thing led to another.

522
00:43:24,868 --> 00:43:27,166
But now, when I look back on it all.

523
00:43:27,237 --> 00:43:28,864
What do you see?

524
00:43:30,608 --> 00:43:33,042
Waste. Failure.

525
00:43:34,211 --> 00:43:35,576
Only that?

526
00:43:36,313 --> 00:43:37,940
Oh, pretty much.

527
00:43:39,416 --> 00:43:42,647
Why don't you think of a time
when you were happy?

528
00:43:43,020 --> 00:43:45,818
Don't patronize me, please.

529
00:43:47,224 --> 00:43:49,692
Why don't you just close your eyes,

530
00:43:50,494 --> 00:43:53,258
and think of a time when you were happy?

531
00:43:55,099 --> 00:43:58,398
It's best, really
if you choose something ordinary.

532
00:44:00,638 --> 00:44:03,630
An ordinary moment during an ordinary day.

533
00:44:22,426 --> 00:44:24,792
Mommy, I want to go home.

534
00:44:25,362 --> 00:44:26,351
Oh, honey...

535
00:44:26,430 --> 00:44:27,692
Everybody's a critic.

536
00:44:27,765 --> 00:44:29,824
No, I'm a terrible mother.

537
00:44:31,535 --> 00:44:33,867
Connie, sweetheart, I'm so sorry.

538
00:44:33,971 --> 00:44:36,439
Your mommy just can't afford a sitter
today and tonight.

539
00:44:39,143 --> 00:44:42,010
Hey, you know I think
I should take her home.

540
00:44:42,079 --> 00:44:44,104
We got to rehearse, baby.

541
00:44:45,149 --> 00:44:46,844
Give her to me.

542
00:44:47,518 --> 00:44:49,884
I've had three, I know what I'm doing.

543
00:44:53,290 --> 00:44:56,123
Now look here. This is a piano.

544
00:44:56,193 --> 00:45:00,630
And you and me are gonna play it.
And your mama's gonna sing for us.

545
00:45:01,398 --> 00:45:02,797
Here we go.

546
00:45:19,416 --> 00:45:23,113
<i>Time after time</i>

547
00:45:23,420 --> 00:45:27,322
<i>I tell myself that I'm</i>

548
00:45:27,725 --> 00:45:33,459
<i>So lucky to be loving you</i>

549
00:45:34,865 --> 00:45:36,093
Look at Mama.

550
00:45:36,166 --> 00:45:38,293
<i>So lucky</i>

551
00:45:38,368 --> 00:45:43,465
<i>To be the one you run to see</i>

552
00:45:44,007 --> 00:45:46,567
<i>In the evening</i>

553
00:45:46,643 --> 00:45:50,340
<i>When the day is through</i>

554
00:45:52,783 --> 00:45:54,978
What happened to your dress?

555
00:45:56,754 --> 00:45:58,745
What dress would that be?

556
00:46:02,659 --> 00:46:03,785
Hey, Luc.

557
00:46:03,861 --> 00:46:05,328
Hey, Annie.

558
00:46:05,395 --> 00:46:06,953
How's the band?

559
00:46:09,099 --> 00:46:12,500
You know,
working our way up from dumps to dives.

560
00:46:15,205 --> 00:46:17,730
Connie, did you like my song?

561
00:46:19,309 --> 00:46:23,075
I'm Nina, Mom.
Connie went home for a little while.

562
00:46:23,147 --> 00:46:26,913
It wasn't right,
me dragging you around to clubs like that.

563
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:31,815
Are you okay, Mom?

564
00:46:32,556 --> 00:46:34,387
Are you in much pain?

565
00:46:34,458 --> 00:46:36,892
We should let her rest a little, I think.

566
00:46:36,960 --> 00:46:39,986
I want to stay a minute, okay? Just me.

567
00:46:40,631 --> 00:46:41,723
Don't overtire her.

568
00:46:41,799 --> 00:46:43,391
Yeah, five minutes.

569
00:47:03,220 --> 00:47:04,482
Hey, Mom.

570
00:47:07,591 --> 00:47:09,115
How you doing?

571
00:47:10,127 --> 00:47:13,585
Honey, let's not talk about me.
How are you?

572
00:47:15,032 --> 00:47:16,329
I'm okay.

573
00:47:17,434 --> 00:47:18,594
I'm Nina, right?

574
00:47:18,669 --> 00:47:20,227
Of course you are.

575
00:47:20,537 --> 00:47:24,029
You look a little peaked, frankly.
Let me feel your forehead.

576
00:47:24,107 --> 00:47:25,472
I'm fine, really.

577
00:47:26,376 --> 00:47:27,866
No, you're not fine.

578
00:47:28,412 --> 00:47:30,812
I'm fine enough. I'm not the one who's sick.

579
00:47:30,881 --> 00:47:33,247
You're not the one's who's well.

580
00:47:35,586 --> 00:47:36,917
Can I tell you something?

581
00:47:37,187 --> 00:47:38,848
Of course.

582
00:47:40,257 --> 00:47:41,781
I'm pregnant.

583
00:47:43,627 --> 00:47:45,026
Oh, darling!

584
00:47:48,232 --> 00:47:49,597
That's wonderful.

585
00:47:49,666 --> 00:47:52,294
With Luc. Luc's baby.

586
00:47:52,903 --> 00:47:55,929
Our baby. I haven't told him.

587
00:47:57,474 --> 00:47:59,601
I haven't told anybody.

588
00:47:59,676 --> 00:48:02,907
And, Mom, I don't know what to do.

589
00:48:04,414 --> 00:48:06,848
I can't imagine getting rid of it.
I don't think I could do that.

590
00:48:06,917 --> 00:48:11,320
But I can't exactly imagine
being with Luc all my life, either.

591
00:48:11,388 --> 00:48:15,688
I mean, we've been together three years
and I've never felt sure.

592
00:48:17,561 --> 00:48:20,121
And now I'm two months along.

593
00:48:21,798 --> 00:48:25,495
I'm afraid having the baby would be
something I'd regret for the rest of my life.

594
00:48:25,569 --> 00:48:29,266
And I'm afraid not having the baby would be
something I'd regret for the rest of my life.

595
00:48:29,339 --> 00:48:31,500
A baby is a wonderful thing.

596
00:48:36,747 --> 00:48:40,843
You said Harris was your only love.
That's how I want to feel.

597
00:48:45,322 --> 00:48:48,348
Harris showed me how much it can be.

598
00:48:54,631 --> 00:48:55,962
Yeah, go on.

599
00:49:03,941 --> 00:49:06,239
Will you promise me something?

600
00:49:06,610 --> 00:49:09,579
Tomorrow, after Sis marries
Dwight D. Eisenhower...

601
00:49:09,646 --> 00:49:10,772
Stop that.

602
00:49:10,847 --> 00:49:14,374
...we can drive to New York together,
just you and I,

603
00:49:15,385 --> 00:49:16,852
and we go on a bender, you know.

604
00:49:16,920 --> 00:49:21,357
We hit a million clubs, hang around
with criminals and degenerates.

605
00:49:21,625 --> 00:49:24,219
I sing for criminals and degenerates.

606
00:49:24,294 --> 00:49:27,821
Thursdays through Sundays.
They lose their fascination.

607
00:49:28,432 --> 00:49:30,764
Hey, hey. Look. Look.

608
00:49:33,470 --> 00:49:34,994
Do you think there's a message inside?

609
00:49:35,072 --> 00:49:37,302
Sure, how could there not be?

610
00:49:38,408 --> 00:49:41,104
I'll bet you Carl threw a dozen of them
in the water last night

611
00:49:41,178 --> 00:49:43,169
for Lila to find this morning.

612
00:49:43,246 --> 00:49:45,908
No, it's for us. It's for you and me.

613
00:49:46,616 --> 00:49:47,981
Just you wait.

614
00:49:48,051 --> 00:49:51,020
There'll be a note in there
that says something like,

615
00:49:51,922 --> 00:49:54,482
"Lila, I'll love you forever."

616
00:49:55,892 --> 00:49:58,986
I was thinking more like,
"Whoever finds this bottle

617
00:49:59,196 --> 00:50:03,189
"gets to make three wishes."
So you start thinking of wishes.

618
00:50:06,103 --> 00:50:07,229
And?

619
00:50:10,774 --> 00:50:14,335
It's wine. It's really old wine.

620
00:50:15,045 --> 00:50:16,637
Don't drink it.

621
00:50:16,980 --> 00:50:19,107
Annie, I'm not that far gone.

622
00:50:19,182 --> 00:50:22,481
No, I'm sorry. Of course you're not.

623
00:50:41,838 --> 00:50:42,930
Hi.

624
00:50:43,573 --> 00:50:45,268
Look what I found.

625
00:50:45,642 --> 00:50:48,839
Oh, my God, her Queen of the Night dress.

626
00:50:49,546 --> 00:50:51,173
Do you remember her wearing this?

627
00:50:51,248 --> 00:50:52,613
Just barely.

628
00:50:52,682 --> 00:50:55,412
Whenever I think of Mom
I see her in this dress.

629
00:50:55,485 --> 00:50:57,476
Going off to work.

630
00:50:58,088 --> 00:50:59,487
She loved it so much.

631
00:50:59,556 --> 00:51:01,547
In her masochistic way.

632
00:51:01,992 --> 00:51:03,459
In a real way.

633
00:51:03,527 --> 00:51:06,792
Singing at the occasional wedding
was not what she had in mind.

634
00:51:06,863 --> 00:51:10,890
Do you remember
when she took us to hear Peggy Lee

635
00:51:10,967 --> 00:51:12,366
at the Algonquin?

636
00:51:12,436 --> 00:51:13,596
That was awful.

637
00:51:13,670 --> 00:51:15,035
No, it wasn't.

638
00:51:15,105 --> 00:51:16,834
Mom cried, hard.

639
00:51:16,907 --> 00:51:18,704
Because she was moved.

640
00:51:18,775 --> 00:51:21,710
Because she was sitting there
with two little girls in party dresses

641
00:51:21,778 --> 00:51:24,178
and Peggy Lee was the one
up there on the stage.

642
00:51:24,247 --> 00:51:27,273
Just how unhappy
do you need Mom to have been?

643
00:51:28,151 --> 00:51:30,142
Translation, please?

644
00:51:30,220 --> 00:51:32,688
Let's let it go. We're both exhausted.

645
00:51:32,756 --> 00:51:35,452
No. Let's not let it go.

646
00:51:37,961 --> 00:51:39,189
Great.

647
00:51:39,896 --> 00:51:41,056
All right.

648
00:51:41,131 --> 00:51:44,999
It seems to me that you're counting on Mom
to have been as unfulfilled as you are.

649
00:51:45,068 --> 00:51:47,093
And I'm not going to let you do it.
How dare you?

650
00:51:47,170 --> 00:51:50,367
I'm not going to let you badger her
on her deathbed

651
00:51:50,440 --> 00:51:55,309
about supposed old miseries
that are probably, in fact, just fever dreams.

652
00:51:55,378 --> 00:51:59,576
Who are you to tell me I'm unfulfilled?
Whatever the hell that means.

653
00:51:59,649 --> 00:52:01,844
Okay, so you're fulfilled and I'm not.

654
00:52:01,918 --> 00:52:04,352
The fulfilled one has the career
and the husband

655
00:52:04,421 --> 00:52:07,857
and the house and garden which just
happen to be three towns away from Mom.

656
00:52:07,924 --> 00:52:09,050
Mom needed someone close by.

657
00:52:09,126 --> 00:52:10,115
And cleaning women.

658
00:52:10,193 --> 00:52:12,525
You don't know how frail she's been,
these last few years.

659
00:52:12,596 --> 00:52:13,688
You've just breezed in and out.

660
00:52:13,763 --> 00:52:15,822
Family dinners at least three times a week.
And no more sex

661
00:52:15,899 --> 00:52:18,595
because even if you weren't too tired,
the children would probably hear you.

662
00:52:18,668 --> 00:52:19,657
Stop this!

663
00:52:19,736 --> 00:52:20,896
So I hope you'll understand if I tell you

664
00:52:20,971 --> 00:52:25,533
I don't look at you and say to myself, "Hey,
that's one fulfilled woman over there."

665
00:52:25,609 --> 00:52:26,837
Let's talk about your life then.

666
00:52:26,910 --> 00:52:28,309
Okay. Let's.

667
00:52:28,378 --> 00:52:30,812
You've had four different careers.

668
00:52:30,881 --> 00:52:32,906
Go-go dancing didn't count as a career.

669
00:52:32,983 --> 00:52:34,917
You were going to be a real dancer.

670
00:52:34,985 --> 00:52:38,944
Do you have any idea how hard it was
for me to admit that I was not good enough?

671
00:52:39,022 --> 00:52:41,286
I don't think you really tried, not really.

672
00:52:41,358 --> 00:52:43,792
Luc is your umpteenth boyfriend.

673
00:52:43,860 --> 00:52:45,589
How many, exactly, is umpteen?

674
00:52:45,662 --> 00:52:48,256
And you're about to dump him.
I look at you and I think,

675
00:52:48,331 --> 00:52:51,994
"In five years she'll have a different job
and another new boyfriend,

676
00:52:52,068 --> 00:52:54,366
"and five years after that,
she'll have another new job

677
00:52:54,437 --> 00:52:56,132
"and another new boyfriend."
So?

678
00:52:56,206 --> 00:52:59,607
Nothing gets its hooks into you.
You just drift.

679
00:53:00,844 --> 00:53:03,335
Well, something has.

680
00:53:08,685 --> 00:53:10,175
I'm pregnant.

681
00:53:11,254 --> 00:53:12,516
You are?

682
00:53:12,856 --> 00:53:13,845
Uh-huh.

683
00:53:18,595 --> 00:53:22,895
Sweetheart, sit down.

684
00:53:24,167 --> 00:53:26,362
Two months, Con, I can stand.

685
00:53:30,273 --> 00:53:32,070
A little slip-up.

686
00:53:32,375 --> 00:53:35,970
It can happen to even
the most determined commit-ophobes.

687
00:53:36,913 --> 00:53:39,074
Come on, sit down.

688
00:53:40,417 --> 00:53:43,409
Okay, I'll sit if it will make you any happier.

689
00:53:43,486 --> 00:53:44,714
It will.

690
00:53:51,261 --> 00:53:53,422
You could be a great mother.

691
00:53:56,066 --> 00:53:58,694
You really love your kids, don't you?

692
00:54:00,704 --> 00:54:02,467
More than anything.

693
00:54:04,407 --> 00:54:05,704
Got that.

694
00:54:06,643 --> 00:54:09,578
That doesn't mean
they don't drive me crazy.

695
00:54:09,779 --> 00:54:12,714
It doesn't mean
I don't wonder sometimes if...

696
00:54:14,084 --> 00:54:18,350
I should be a surfer chick
with seven stupid boyfriends.

697
00:54:21,758 --> 00:54:23,248
Got that, too.

698
00:54:55,892 --> 00:54:58,622
Will you not get mad if I say something?

699
00:55:01,398 --> 00:55:03,025
I'll do my best.

700
00:55:03,733 --> 00:55:06,201
If you go on being the bad girl,

701
00:55:06,636 --> 00:55:11,266
if you insist on screwing up everything
and everyone that comes your way,

702
00:55:12,275 --> 00:55:15,369
there's a very real chance
you'll end up alone.

703
00:55:19,582 --> 00:55:22,142
Nina, I'm sorry.

704
00:55:24,354 --> 00:55:25,446
See,

705
00:55:27,424 --> 00:55:29,255
at least I'm not mad.

706
00:56:32,856 --> 00:56:34,289
Hello there.

707
00:56:35,125 --> 00:56:37,593
What am I doing here? Who are you?

708
00:56:37,761 --> 00:56:40,025
I'm the night nurse. Remember?

709
00:56:42,599 --> 00:56:44,863
You said you've met my husbands.

710
00:56:45,068 --> 00:56:47,093
No, I'm afraid I haven't.

711
00:56:47,737 --> 00:56:51,173
I married Ralph Haverford.
He was the best man.

712
00:56:51,241 --> 00:56:54,642
Isn't that strange.
Do you think I took it literally?

713
00:56:55,612 --> 00:56:57,409
That I couldn't say.

714
00:56:57,680 --> 00:57:00,945
I left him on the sidewalk
like a piece of chewing gum.

715
00:57:01,017 --> 00:57:03,076
Some maid of honor, right?

716
00:57:04,120 --> 00:57:05,951
Are you feeling better now?

717
00:57:06,022 --> 00:57:10,652
Then I married Phil, Nina's father.
He had such nice hair.

718
00:57:13,430 --> 00:57:15,125
Nice hair is nice.

719
00:57:17,434 --> 00:57:18,867
Are you married?

720
00:57:18,935 --> 00:57:20,197
Yes, I am.

721
00:57:20,770 --> 00:57:23,238
Do you love him in that crazy way?

722
00:57:24,808 --> 00:57:27,368
We've been married almost 40 years.

723
00:57:27,944 --> 00:57:31,971
I've been married for 40 years.
More than 40. To Harris.

724
00:57:32,048 --> 00:57:34,881
I just haven't seen him the whole time
we've been married.

725
00:57:34,951 --> 00:57:38,717
Well, maybe that's the best way.

726
00:57:42,692 --> 00:57:45,684
Is there anyone special
you'd like me to call?

727
00:58:15,492 --> 00:58:16,754
Oh, Sis.

728
00:58:22,398 --> 00:58:23,660
You nervous?

729
00:58:24,133 --> 00:58:25,794
Yeah, a little.

730
00:58:25,869 --> 00:58:27,393
You look fantastic.

731
00:58:27,470 --> 00:58:28,528
Just breathe.

732
00:58:29,639 --> 00:58:32,767
Yeah, okay. All right.

733
00:58:38,181 --> 00:58:39,443
Peach...

734
00:58:49,792 --> 00:58:52,386
You think maybe Peach and Pip
could be next?

735
00:58:52,462 --> 00:58:53,895
Pip's a little stuffy.

736
00:58:54,230 --> 00:58:55,754
Peach likes stuffy.

737
00:58:56,232 --> 00:58:58,427
Hey. We're on.

738
00:59:02,872 --> 00:59:05,636
And then there's the question of Buddy
for Lizzie.

739
00:59:05,708 --> 00:59:07,801
Do you really think that
everybody in your wedding party

740
00:59:07,877 --> 00:59:09,936
should just marry everybody else?

741
00:59:10,179 --> 00:59:14,309
No. But it would be nice
if my wedding inspired another one.

742
00:59:15,285 --> 00:59:16,582
Ann.

743
00:59:32,886 --> 00:59:34,877
Are you ready, sweetheart?

744
00:59:36,790 --> 00:59:39,384
Yes, ready.

745
01:00:46,927 --> 01:00:51,159
"We are such stuff as dreams are made on."

746
01:01:21,995 --> 01:01:22,984
Are you ready?

747
01:01:23,063 --> 01:01:24,360
I guess so.

748
01:01:38,044 --> 01:01:40,012
<i>...sing Time after Time.</i>

749
01:01:40,881 --> 01:01:42,508
<i>Time after Time.</i>

750
01:01:44,150 --> 01:01:46,744
<i>Hi, everybody. Hi.</i>

751
01:01:51,124 --> 01:01:54,150
<i>When Lila asked me to sing at her wedding,</i>

752
01:01:54,227 --> 01:01:57,424
<i>I told her that I usually only sing
for drunks and tourists.</i>

753
01:01:57,497 --> 01:02:00,432
And we're not tourists.

754
01:02:02,636 --> 01:02:04,661
<i>But she wouldn't take no.</i>

755
01:02:04,738 --> 01:02:08,902
<i>So, Lila, this is for you.</i>

756
01:02:20,086 --> 01:02:25,888
<i>What good are words I say to you</i>

757
01:02:26,960 --> 01:02:30,691
<i>They can't convey to you</i>

758
01:02:31,398 --> 01:02:34,731
<i>What's in my heart</i>

759
01:02:35,936 --> 01:02:42,364
<i>If you could hear instead</i>

760
01:02:43,410 --> 01:02:50,373
<i>The things I've left unsaid</i>

761
01:02:54,054 --> 01:02:57,114
<i>Time after time</i>

762
01:02:57,657 --> 01:03:00,182
<i>I tell myself</i>

763
01:03:00,293 --> 01:03:03,558
<i>That I'm so lucky</i>

764
01:03:03,630 --> 01:03:08,090
<i>To be loving you</i>

765
01:03:10,770 --> 01:03:14,968
<i>So lucky to be</i>

766
01:03:15,208 --> 01:03:18,666
<i>The one you run to see</i>

767
01:03:18,912 --> 01:03:21,107
<i>In the evening</i>

768
01:03:21,181 --> 01:03:25,618
<i>When the day is through</i>

769
01:03:45,071 --> 01:03:49,599
<i>I only know what I know</i>

770
01:03:50,276 --> 01:03:54,144
<i>The passing years will show</i>

771
01:03:54,481 --> 01:04:01,444
<i>You kept my love so young, so new</i>

772
01:04:03,456 --> 01:04:07,290
<i>And time after time</i>

773
01:04:07,761 --> 01:04:12,198
<i>You'll hear me say that I'm</i>

774
01:04:13,867 --> 01:04:20,170
<i>so lucky to be loving</i>

775
01:04:23,343 --> 01:04:27,507
<i>you</i>

776
01:04:58,511 --> 01:05:00,138
Where did you go?

777
01:05:00,213 --> 01:05:01,703
I snuck out. I felt like a fool.

778
01:05:01,781 --> 01:05:04,477
No, you were nothing like a fool.
You were a hero.

779
01:05:04,551 --> 01:05:07,384
You were the hero. I hit most of the notes.

780
01:05:07,454 --> 01:05:11,515
No, honestly, I didn't sound that great.
I don't mind that.

781
01:05:14,561 --> 01:05:19,123
There was something about being up there,
just now, singing that song for Lila.

782
01:05:21,901 --> 01:05:23,368
I don't know.

783
01:05:25,271 --> 01:05:28,365
I've always thought of myself as just sort of
singing into the room, I guess,

784
01:05:28,441 --> 01:05:32,810
but, I mean doing it specifically for her,

785
01:05:36,015 --> 01:05:37,812
it was so different.

786
01:05:38,885 --> 01:05:40,785
You got a gift, kid.

787
01:05:43,089 --> 01:05:47,753
You know, honestly, for the first time,
right now, I feel like

788
01:05:49,162 --> 01:05:50,629
maybe I do.

789
01:05:54,667 --> 01:05:56,999
I want to be good at this, you know?

790
01:05:57,070 --> 01:06:02,633
Not just all right but really, really good.

791
01:06:06,179 --> 01:06:08,147
I want to sing on Mars one day.

792
01:06:09,449 --> 01:06:14,182
If you sing on Mars, I'll shut down
my practice and fly up to see you.

793
01:06:15,788 --> 01:06:17,483
Do you think we need another star for this?

794
01:06:17,557 --> 01:06:19,718
Yeah, I do.

795
01:06:20,660 --> 01:06:24,926
Well, I think it should be close to the one
that you picked out last night.

796
01:06:26,533 --> 01:06:29,468
There's a nice one, just south of it.

797
01:06:30,537 --> 01:06:31,526
Oh.

798
01:06:32,672 --> 01:06:35,140
That's rather modest, don't you think?

799
01:06:35,208 --> 01:06:38,735
Well, there's lots of stars,
this is only our second one.

800
01:06:51,558 --> 01:06:52,957
Hey there.

801
01:06:55,895 --> 01:06:58,455
Whoops. Am I interrupting something?

802
01:06:58,531 --> 01:07:00,055
No, Buddy.

803
01:07:04,337 --> 01:07:06,498
Tonight it's all about love, right?

804
01:07:07,407 --> 01:07:09,534
In all its forms and guises.

805
01:07:13,213 --> 01:07:15,306
<i>Time after time</i>

806
01:07:15,648 --> 01:07:19,846
<i>I tell myself that I'm so lucky</i>

807
01:07:24,457 --> 01:07:28,621
Come on, let's dance.
No, no, all three of us. Come on.

808
01:07:32,665 --> 01:07:35,190
Hey, I've finally had an idea for my novel.

809
01:07:35,268 --> 01:07:36,326
Shoot.

810
01:07:36,402 --> 01:07:39,769
It's about a gangster
who's in love with a rich girl.

811
01:07:39,839 --> 01:07:42,171
<i>Honey, that's The Great Gatsby.</i>

812
01:07:43,409 --> 01:07:44,535
Damn.

813
01:07:45,645 --> 01:07:49,672
Well, in my version, they all get married
and live happily ever after,

814
01:07:49,749 --> 01:07:51,512
<i>and it'll be the fun Great Gatsby.</i>

815
01:07:51,584 --> 01:07:53,449
Why not?
Harris, isn't Ann great?

816
01:07:53,519 --> 01:07:54,679
Yeah, she's okay.

817
01:07:54,754 --> 01:07:56,551
We've been friends since college.

818
01:07:56,623 --> 01:07:58,386
Ann and Lila and me.

819
01:07:59,692 --> 01:08:01,557
Now that Lila's a wife,

820
01:08:03,529 --> 01:08:05,360
it's just Ann and me.

821
01:08:05,965 --> 01:08:07,227
Buddy.

822
01:08:07,300 --> 01:08:08,699
Ann.

823
01:08:10,937 --> 01:08:13,064
Hey, Buddy boy,
maybe it's time to go...

824
01:08:15,642 --> 01:08:16,631
Whoops.

825
01:08:18,111 --> 01:08:21,774
Terribly sorry, old chap.
It's the wine. It's the wine.

826
01:08:22,315 --> 01:08:23,748
Hey, Buddy, come back.

827
01:08:23,816 --> 01:08:25,283
As you were. As you were.

828
01:08:25,351 --> 01:08:29,344
It's just a little battle fatigue.
I'm off to the front line again.

829
01:08:31,424 --> 01:08:33,915
He won't remember that in the morning.

830
01:08:33,993 --> 01:08:35,483
I'm not so sure.

831
01:08:39,766 --> 01:08:41,097
Ann!

832
01:08:41,167 --> 01:08:43,658
Ann Grant! Maid of honor at large!

833
01:08:51,544 --> 01:08:54,638
Now, we don't have to tell you
about the birds and the bees, do we?

834
01:08:54,714 --> 01:08:56,807
Sorry, bad bridesmaid.

835
01:08:57,784 --> 01:08:59,615
Lila, you're perfect.

836
01:08:59,919 --> 01:09:01,887
The carriage awaits.

837
01:09:09,762 --> 01:09:11,457
Mrs. Carl Ross.

838
01:09:12,165 --> 01:09:13,632
Mmm-hmm.

839
01:09:14,267 --> 01:09:20,570
Ann you didn't mention anything,
to anyone, I mean, about this morning.

840
01:09:21,207 --> 01:09:22,333
What?

841
01:09:23,009 --> 01:09:25,534
You know.
The bride's brief bout of hysteria.

842
01:09:25,611 --> 01:09:27,306
Oh, no, of course not.

843
01:09:27,747 --> 01:09:29,112
Good.

844
01:09:29,182 --> 01:09:32,310
I don't want people to get
the wrong impression.

845
01:09:35,154 --> 01:09:38,920
Lila, if you want me to,
I'll take you out of here right now.

846
01:09:40,126 --> 01:09:42,492
I will, I'll do all the talking.

847
01:09:43,196 --> 01:09:45,630
I'll put you in a car
and I'll just drive you away.

848
01:09:45,698 --> 01:09:47,495
Ann.
I'm serious.

849
01:09:47,567 --> 01:09:51,594
It's not too late.
You just say the word and I'll take you away.

850
01:09:57,877 --> 01:10:02,439
Come visit us in Boston, when we get back.
Do you promise?

851
01:10:04,584 --> 01:10:05,881
Sure.

852
01:10:07,286 --> 01:10:08,947
Okay.
I promise.

853
01:10:11,591 --> 01:10:14,822
Well, off I go.

854
01:10:15,928 --> 01:10:17,020
Come here.

855
01:10:25,605 --> 01:10:26,936
Goodbye, Lila.

856
01:10:35,248 --> 01:10:36,442
You know what it's time for now?

857
01:10:36,516 --> 01:10:37,847
The Plunge.

858
01:10:37,917 --> 01:10:39,441
You got it. Come on.

859
01:10:39,519 --> 01:10:41,214
I think I'm going to skip the Plunge.

860
01:10:41,287 --> 01:10:42,777
You can't. It's a tradition.

861
01:10:42,855 --> 01:10:45,790
You don't have to jump, but you do have
to come cheer for the fools who do.

862
01:10:45,858 --> 01:10:48,850
I'm one of the fools.
You'll cheer for me, won't you?

863
01:10:48,928 --> 01:10:50,122
Have you seen Buddy?

864
01:10:50,196 --> 01:10:51,857
Yeah, a while ago, come on.

865
01:10:51,931 --> 01:10:54,058
You know, I'm gonna come in a while,
you go on ahead.

866
01:10:54,133 --> 01:10:55,327
You sure?

867
01:10:55,401 --> 01:10:56,595
Fifteen minutes, tops.

868
01:10:57,470 --> 01:10:58,528
I'll be there.

869
01:10:58,604 --> 01:10:59,662
Okay.

870
01:11:10,983 --> 01:11:12,541
There you are.

871
01:11:31,671 --> 01:11:33,332
I kissed Harris.

872
01:11:34,307 --> 01:11:35,467
I know you did.

873
01:11:35,541 --> 01:11:39,978
The thing is, I'm not that way.

874
01:11:42,882 --> 01:11:44,611
It wouldn't matter if you were.

875
01:11:44,684 --> 01:11:46,982
Oh, yeah. Isn't it pretty to think so?

876
01:11:48,387 --> 01:11:51,356
Hemingway got that line first, the bastard.

877
01:11:52,358 --> 01:11:53,450
Buddy, it's all right...

878
01:11:53,526 --> 01:11:54,618
You know, Lila and I,

879
01:11:54,694 --> 01:11:57,094
we've both always had this sort of

880
01:11:59,665 --> 01:12:01,394
crush on Harris.

881
01:12:03,569 --> 01:12:07,232
You know, Lila's been in love with him
pretty much all her life.

882
01:12:07,740 --> 01:12:09,674
But it wouldn't do for her to,

883
01:12:10,743 --> 01:12:12,472
you know, get involved
with one of the servants.

884
01:12:12,545 --> 01:12:14,240
That's ridiculous.

885
01:12:15,648 --> 01:12:17,377
Not to some people.

886
01:12:20,553 --> 01:12:23,454
Hey, want to see something
really ridiculous?

887
01:12:23,823 --> 01:12:24,949
Okay.

888
01:12:31,731 --> 01:12:33,221
What's this?

889
01:12:34,233 --> 01:12:39,830
It's a note you passed me, junior year.
Introduction to Philosophy.

890
01:12:41,107 --> 01:12:42,096
I can't read it.

891
01:12:42,174 --> 01:12:44,904
No, that's because the ink is so faded,
it says,

892
01:12:46,612 --> 01:12:50,343
"Wittgenstein, Schmittgenstein,
what's for lunch?"

893
01:12:51,584 --> 01:12:52,983
That's it?

894
01:12:53,953 --> 01:12:55,511
Yeah, that's it.

895
01:12:56,756 --> 01:12:59,122
And you brought it to the wedding?

896
01:12:59,525 --> 01:13:00,651
No, no.

897
01:13:02,461 --> 01:13:05,225
I've had it in my pocket for, let's see,

898
01:13:06,732 --> 01:13:08,256
four years now.

899
01:13:11,637 --> 01:13:12,763
What?

900
01:13:13,039 --> 01:13:16,770
Yeah, just jammed it in my pocket
that day in class

901
01:13:17,710 --> 01:13:21,976
and then that night in my dorm room
I took it out, put it on my bureau

902
01:13:22,048 --> 01:13:26,109
with my keys and my loose change
and everything.

903
01:13:28,087 --> 01:13:32,387
And then the next morning,
for some reason,

904
01:13:33,192 --> 01:13:37,390
I put it back in my pocket
with my keys and my loose change.

905
01:13:41,634 --> 01:13:44,398
And I've been carrying it around ever since.

906
01:13:45,972 --> 01:13:47,735
I don't understand.

907
01:13:49,742 --> 01:13:51,175
Yes, you do.

908
01:13:53,179 --> 01:13:55,647
Buddy, you've had a lot to drink.

909
01:13:58,551 --> 01:14:01,247
I'm not even sure of who to be jealous of.

910
01:14:01,320 --> 01:14:03,379
You're not even going to remember this
in the morning.

911
01:14:03,456 --> 01:14:08,553
What if you and I just sang

912
01:14:09,528 --> 01:14:11,291
and laughed together

913
01:14:12,765 --> 01:14:14,858
for the rest of our lives?

914
01:14:17,103 --> 01:14:19,628
What if we had a few goofy kids
who got our jokes

915
01:14:19,705 --> 01:14:22,435
and taught us some new songs, huh?

916
01:14:28,614 --> 01:14:30,514
It wouldn't work.

917
01:14:50,169 --> 01:14:51,693
Not for you.

918
01:14:52,638 --> 01:14:56,802
No, honey, not for me.

919
01:14:58,944 --> 01:15:00,309
I'm sorry.

920
01:15:08,788 --> 01:15:10,813
Can I have the note back?

921
01:15:37,583 --> 01:15:39,016
Come on, Pip!

922
01:15:39,085 --> 01:15:40,780
Pip! Pip! Pip!

923
01:15:52,064 --> 01:15:54,089
You're just in time, I'm next.

924
01:15:54,734 --> 01:15:56,634
What fools we mortals be.

925
01:16:01,240 --> 01:16:04,437
Come on, Peach! Peach is next!

926
01:16:07,346 --> 01:16:10,110
Peach! Peach! Peach!

927
01:16:10,716 --> 01:16:11,978
Ann, hi.

928
01:16:12,885 --> 01:16:16,787
Hey, Ralph, do you think you could help me
keep an eye on Buddy?

929
01:16:16,856 --> 01:16:19,484
I'd rather help you keep an eye on me.

930
01:16:23,929 --> 01:16:26,227
Finally! A girl with some guts!

931
01:16:38,778 --> 01:16:40,541
Whoo-hoo!

932
01:16:43,582 --> 01:16:44,844
Yeah!

933
01:16:46,685 --> 01:16:48,175
Buddy! Buddy! Buddy!

934
01:16:48,554 --> 01:16:51,079
Hey. Could you help me get Buddy to bed.

935
01:16:51,157 --> 01:16:55,685
Ann, will you do something for me?
Forget about Buddy for five minutes.

936
01:16:56,662 --> 01:16:58,459
I would be glad to.

937
01:17:02,902 --> 01:17:05,063
Buddy! Buddy!

938
01:17:10,209 --> 01:17:11,676
Yeah!

939
01:17:18,918 --> 01:17:21,853
Buddy! Buddy! Buddy!

940
01:17:33,699 --> 01:17:36,998
Buddy! Buddy! Buddy!

941
01:17:42,908 --> 01:17:44,432
Buddy!
Hey, Buddy!

942
01:17:49,715 --> 01:17:50,909
Buddy!

943
01:17:50,983 --> 01:17:52,245
Buddy!

944
01:17:52,318 --> 01:17:53,910
Buddy!
Buddy!

945
01:17:59,892 --> 01:18:01,450
Move! Move!

946
01:18:10,970 --> 01:18:12,164
Buddy!

947
01:18:12,771 --> 01:18:13,760
Can you see him?

948
01:18:13,839 --> 01:18:14,999
No, nothing!

949
01:18:15,574 --> 01:18:17,007
Where is he?

950
01:18:18,611 --> 01:18:19,908
Do you see him?

951
01:18:19,979 --> 01:18:21,139
No!

952
01:18:24,817 --> 01:18:26,114
Buddy!

953
01:18:26,785 --> 01:18:28,685
Please, Buddy, be okay.

954
01:18:33,959 --> 01:18:35,221
Buddy!

955
01:18:36,228 --> 01:18:37,820
Please, Buddy, be okay.

956
01:18:44,236 --> 01:18:46,397
Somebody lose something?

957
01:18:47,039 --> 01:18:48,336
Oh, Jesus.

958
01:18:50,976 --> 01:18:52,637
He's up here!

959
01:18:54,280 --> 01:18:55,611
It's kind of salty.

960
01:18:57,516 --> 01:18:58,574
Ow.

961
01:18:58,651 --> 01:19:01,245
You're not a hero. You're pathetic!

962
01:19:01,320 --> 01:19:02,378
Oh, Ann.

963
01:19:02,454 --> 01:19:05,446
Have some guts! Go live your own life!

964
01:19:05,524 --> 01:19:06,752
What? This isn't it?

965
01:19:06,825 --> 01:19:09,988
Write a first line
and then write a second one.

966
01:19:10,062 --> 01:19:13,088
Kiss men if you want to!
Horrify your parents!

967
01:19:13,165 --> 01:19:14,154
Annie?

968
01:19:14,233 --> 01:19:15,495
Be a man!

969
01:19:15,567 --> 01:19:17,660
Just leave me out of it!

970
01:19:18,938 --> 01:19:21,270
Don't carry around some...

971
01:19:21,340 --> 01:19:24,776
Some stupid note I wrote you years ago!

972
01:19:27,746 --> 01:19:31,876
You're not interested in me.
You just have this idea of me.

973
01:19:33,619 --> 01:19:36,144
Have the nerve to admit it, and just

974
01:19:38,357 --> 01:19:40,325
leave me alone.

975
01:19:50,502 --> 01:19:52,697
Hell, I got the note all wet.

976
01:19:55,808 --> 01:19:57,332
Ann! Ann!

977
01:19:57,409 --> 01:19:59,001
Take me out of here, okay?

978
01:19:59,078 --> 01:20:00,306
Okay, where do you want to go?

979
01:20:00,379 --> 01:20:02,108
Somewhere far away from all these people.

980
01:20:02,181 --> 01:20:04,843
Okay. I got it, follow me.

981
01:20:16,929 --> 01:20:18,191
Where are we going?

982
01:20:18,263 --> 01:20:19,924
It's a surprise.

983
01:20:29,508 --> 01:20:33,000
Ann, I just had one more thing...

984
01:20:34,546 --> 01:20:37,071
Just one more thing I wanted to say.

985
01:21:25,230 --> 01:21:27,130
Welcome to my hideout.

986
01:21:34,573 --> 01:21:36,268
<i>Gray's Anatomy?</i>

987
01:21:37,476 --> 01:21:41,572
I've known I've wanted to be a doctor
since I was eight years old.

988
01:21:43,449 --> 01:21:46,384
You are the most serious man I've ever met.

989
01:21:48,187 --> 01:21:50,747
I guess I'm not a lot of fun.

990
01:21:52,191 --> 01:21:54,853
I didn't say you weren't a lot of fun.

991
01:21:58,664 --> 01:22:00,495
Your shirt's all wet.

992
01:22:41,974 --> 01:22:43,407
What's this?

993
01:22:43,842 --> 01:22:46,037
It's just what's in the air.

994
01:22:50,282 --> 01:22:51,840
Has it always been like this?

995
01:22:51,917 --> 01:22:53,248
Oh, yes.

996
01:23:01,660 --> 01:23:03,651
I don't think I like it.

997
01:23:17,643 --> 01:23:19,076
What a night!

998
01:23:19,144 --> 01:23:20,168
Where's Ann?

999
01:23:20,245 --> 01:23:21,678
Where's Harris?

1000
01:23:51,076 --> 01:23:53,237
Now there's a pretty sight.

1001
01:23:57,249 --> 01:24:00,116
Hey, wild man, time to call it a night.

1002
01:24:03,088 --> 01:24:04,612
Oh, my goodness!

1003
01:24:04,690 --> 01:24:05,952
What?

1004
01:24:06,024 --> 01:24:08,788
Blood. It's all over. Oh, my goodness!

1005
01:24:11,663 --> 01:24:12,857
Jesus!

1006
01:24:14,466 --> 01:24:15,592
He's breathing.
What happened?

1007
01:24:15,667 --> 01:24:17,191
I'll go call a doctor!

1008
01:24:18,103 --> 01:24:19,798
Wait, Harris is a doctor!

1009
01:24:19,871 --> 01:24:21,463
Where's Harris? Can't be far away.
Harris!

1010
01:24:21,540 --> 01:24:22,837
Harris!

1011
01:24:22,908 --> 01:24:24,432
Harris!

1012
01:24:25,444 --> 01:24:27,309
Harris!
Harris!

1013
01:24:29,181 --> 01:24:30,773
We got to get him to a hospital!
Harris!

1014
01:24:30,849 --> 01:24:32,248
We can't move him.

1015
01:24:32,317 --> 01:24:34,911
Hang on, Buddy, just hang on.
Everything's going to be okay!

1016
01:24:34,987 --> 01:24:36,648
He's holding something in his hand.

1017
01:24:36,722 --> 01:24:40,556
What is it, Buddy? It's just some gunk.
Wet paper or something.

1018
01:24:41,059 --> 01:24:42,356
Let's go, let's go.

1019
01:24:43,061 --> 01:24:45,086
Legs, legs, legs.

1020
01:24:57,209 --> 01:24:58,471
My God.

1021
01:25:00,145 --> 01:25:02,136
Buddy's right, you know.

1022
01:25:02,214 --> 01:25:04,546
About what?
About you.

1023
01:25:04,883 --> 01:25:08,876
You're brilliant. You're gonna be famous.

1024
01:25:12,824 --> 01:25:15,190
Hardly anyone gets to be famous.

1025
01:25:20,899 --> 01:25:22,730
You're famous to me.

1026
01:25:55,500 --> 01:25:56,865
Hey, Mom.

1027
01:25:58,637 --> 01:26:02,630
I found your dress. It's still as beautiful.

1028
01:26:04,443 --> 01:26:06,707
It's just like I remember it.

1029
01:26:08,647 --> 01:26:12,640
I actually hated you sometimes
when you put on that dress.

1030
01:26:13,819 --> 01:26:17,084
And I didn't really understand

1031
01:26:17,489 --> 01:26:22,051
until I had Ethan and Chloe. About...

1032
01:26:23,795 --> 01:26:25,057
Well, how...

1033
01:26:26,498 --> 01:26:29,262
It seems like you break
your children's hearts

1034
01:26:30,168 --> 01:26:31,897
no matter what you do.

1035
01:26:37,509 --> 01:26:41,502
Whether you sing in clubs at night
or just stay home.

1036
01:26:43,515 --> 01:26:48,748
And you start to wonder which mistakes
of yours they're going to forget,

1037
01:26:48,820 --> 01:26:54,417
and which ones they'll still be talking about
for years after you're gone.

1038
01:27:03,402 --> 01:27:04,664
Um...

1039
01:27:05,771 --> 01:27:08,968
I've been meaning to tell you
what I've learned

1040
01:27:11,109 --> 01:27:13,669
about how it must have been for you.

1041
01:27:16,748 --> 01:27:19,774
And now I'm afraid
I may have waited too long.

1042
01:27:23,422 --> 01:27:26,721
So, do you think

1043
01:27:27,592 --> 01:27:30,527
you could be your old self again?

1044
01:27:31,797 --> 01:27:34,095
It would mean so much to me.

1045
01:27:36,234 --> 01:27:37,963
I want you back.

1046
01:28:24,349 --> 01:28:26,214
We're in trouble now.

1047
01:28:26,685 --> 01:28:28,550
Maybe we should just keep going.

1048
01:28:28,620 --> 01:28:30,611
Where could we go from here?

1049
01:28:30,689 --> 01:28:33,954
The boat. We could sail to Barbados.

1050
01:28:34,793 --> 01:28:36,055
I've never been to Barbados.

1051
01:28:36,127 --> 01:28:37,492
See, me neither.

1052
01:28:37,562 --> 01:28:40,395
We should probably stop in and say
goodbye to the Wittenborns, though,

1053
01:28:40,465 --> 01:28:42,933
since we'll be stealing their boat.

1054
01:28:46,505 --> 01:28:47,767
I've got a funny feeling suddenly.

1055
01:28:47,839 --> 01:28:48,863
What?

1056
01:28:50,842 --> 01:28:53,970
I don't want to go back into that house.
I don't. Not for one minute.

1057
01:28:54,045 --> 01:28:55,910
It's just a formality.

1058
01:28:59,918 --> 01:29:01,112
Kiss me.

1059
01:29:01,186 --> 01:29:02,380
Gladly.

1060
01:31:39,678 --> 01:31:41,077
You'll come back for me then?

1061
01:31:41,146 --> 01:31:42,636
Yes, ma'am.

1062
01:31:44,315 --> 01:31:45,577
Hello?

1063
01:31:46,584 --> 01:31:47,608
Hello.

1064
01:31:47,686 --> 01:31:48,914
Are you Ann's daughters?

1065
01:31:49,354 --> 01:31:50,412
Yeah. I'm Nina.

1066
01:31:50,488 --> 01:31:51,921
I'm Constance.

1067
01:31:52,991 --> 01:31:56,358
I'm Lila Ross.
I'm an old friend of your mother's.

1068
01:31:56,428 --> 01:31:57,656
Hi.

1069
01:31:58,930 --> 01:32:01,660
I got a telephone call from her nurse.

1070
01:32:01,733 --> 01:32:04,930
She said your mother was very, very ill
so I came right away.

1071
01:32:05,003 --> 01:32:06,493
I hope it's not inconvenient.

1072
01:32:06,571 --> 01:32:08,471
No, not at all. Come in.

1073
01:32:21,186 --> 01:32:23,017
Just up here.

1074
01:32:54,953 --> 01:32:56,045
Ann?

1075
01:33:13,138 --> 01:33:18,132
Are you an angel? Because frankly,
I don't want any damn angels in here.

1076
01:33:20,512 --> 01:33:23,572
Hardly. It's Lila.

1077
01:33:27,685 --> 01:33:29,846
Oh, my God!

1078
01:33:33,424 --> 01:33:34,857
Oh, gosh.

1079
01:33:37,729 --> 01:33:41,688
It's been a long, long time.
Years and years and years.

1080
01:33:41,866 --> 01:33:43,231
Mmm-hmm.

1081
01:33:47,238 --> 01:33:48,227
Yes.

1082
01:33:59,417 --> 01:34:00,406
Lila.

1083
01:34:10,361 --> 01:34:13,353
It's terribly hard, being so sick.

1084
01:34:15,867 --> 01:34:18,097
I watched Carl go through it.

1085
01:34:19,504 --> 01:34:21,096
Is Carl...

1086
01:34:23,241 --> 01:34:24,333
Gone.

1087
01:34:26,377 --> 01:34:28,004
Seven years now.

1088
01:34:31,883 --> 01:34:32,872
Hmm.

1089
01:34:36,621 --> 01:34:38,521
We have three children.

1090
01:34:38,690 --> 01:34:40,681
Three? I have two. Two girls.

1091
01:34:40,758 --> 01:34:44,751
I know. I saw the girls downstairs.

1092
01:34:45,230 --> 01:34:46,959
They're so lovely.

1093
01:34:49,767 --> 01:34:51,860
Do you still know Harris?

1094
01:34:56,107 --> 01:34:58,473
In a Christmas card sort of way.

1095
01:34:58,843 --> 01:35:02,210
He met a girl. In Shelburne Falls. A nurse.

1096
01:35:03,181 --> 01:35:04,705
Yes, I know.

1097
01:35:08,519 --> 01:35:10,350
He wrote me a letter.

1098
01:35:10,588 --> 01:35:11,577
Mmm-hmm.

1099
01:35:12,557 --> 01:35:13,785
I know.

1100
01:35:17,562 --> 01:35:20,030
I thought there'd be so many chances.

1101
01:35:23,001 --> 01:35:24,730
There were some.

1102
01:35:26,537 --> 01:35:27,629
But not...

1103
01:35:41,552 --> 01:35:43,713
No one ever moved me like...

1104
01:36:02,907 --> 01:36:04,499
There, there.

1105
01:36:07,178 --> 01:36:08,577
La, la, la.

1106
01:36:13,451 --> 01:36:15,248
Have you been happy?

1107
01:36:19,190 --> 01:36:20,748
At times.

1108
01:36:22,160 --> 01:36:24,492
At times I've been very unhappy.

1109
01:36:26,064 --> 01:36:27,463
Is that it?

1110
01:36:28,533 --> 01:36:31,627
I never expected as much as you did.

1111
01:36:31,970 --> 01:36:33,733
I expected so much.

1112
01:36:35,139 --> 01:36:36,629
Yes, you did.

1113
01:36:38,843 --> 01:36:40,640
And you got so much.

1114
01:36:41,879 --> 01:36:45,940
Two bad marriages and
I didn't turn out to be such a great singer.

1115
01:36:48,252 --> 01:36:50,152
You sang at my wedding.

1116
01:36:50,955 --> 01:36:53,947
A century or two ago.
Oh, yes.

1117
01:36:57,428 --> 01:36:59,555
My God, you were wonderful.

1118
01:37:01,733 --> 01:37:06,397
You were so beautiful standing up there.

1119
01:37:07,405 --> 01:37:11,967
So brave and strong,

1120
01:37:12,877 --> 01:37:14,344
and full of hope.

1121
01:37:17,515 --> 01:37:19,244
It was nothing.

1122
01:37:20,618 --> 01:37:22,813
Well, it was something to me.

1123
01:37:27,859 --> 01:37:29,759
I think about it.

1124
01:37:29,827 --> 01:37:31,124
My God!

1125
01:37:31,195 --> 01:37:32,184
Mmm-hmm.

1126
01:37:33,031 --> 01:37:35,192
I still think about it.

1127
01:37:38,603 --> 01:37:39,661
Really?

1128
01:37:42,073 --> 01:37:43,165
Yeah.

1129
01:38:16,207 --> 01:38:17,469
Harris?

1130
01:38:17,942 --> 01:38:19,170
Harris!

1131
01:38:22,346 --> 01:38:23,643
Ann?

1132
01:38:23,714 --> 01:38:25,477
Hi. Hi.

1133
01:38:27,318 --> 01:38:29,013
How are you?

1134
01:38:29,087 --> 01:38:31,317
Okay. I'm fine.

1135
01:38:32,457 --> 01:38:34,322
I can't believe this.

1136
01:38:35,193 --> 01:38:37,661
I'm moving to Los Angeles.

1137
01:38:38,729 --> 01:38:40,356
We're going back to Shelburne Falls.

1138
01:38:40,431 --> 01:38:44,697
We just came in for the weekend,
to see my wife's brother.

1139
01:38:50,041 --> 01:38:51,668
That's your son?

1140
01:38:52,043 --> 01:38:53,476
Buddy.

1141
01:38:57,115 --> 01:38:58,776
Three years old.

1142
01:39:00,852 --> 01:39:02,012
Harris.

1143
01:39:02,086 --> 01:39:03,246
How about if I introduce you?

1144
01:39:03,321 --> 01:39:05,915
Oh, no, no. I've... I've got a plane to catch.

1145
01:39:11,295 --> 01:39:12,887
You look great.

1146
01:39:12,964 --> 01:39:13,988
So do you.

1147
01:39:16,234 --> 01:39:18,031
I have a daughter.

1148
01:39:18,536 --> 01:39:19,935
Wonderful.

1149
01:39:21,105 --> 01:39:22,800
You still singing?

1150
01:39:23,808 --> 01:39:25,298
Not right now.

1151
01:39:26,878 --> 01:39:28,175
Why did you stop?

1152
01:39:28,246 --> 01:39:29,338
I got married.

1153
01:39:29,413 --> 01:39:31,574
And I married Ralph Haverford.

1154
01:39:31,883 --> 01:39:32,872
Oh.

1155
01:39:33,251 --> 01:39:35,310
And then I had the baby,

1156
01:39:35,887 --> 01:39:41,223
and, you know,
one thing just sort of leads to another.

1157
01:39:44,095 --> 01:39:46,325
I have to tell you something.

1158
01:39:52,103 --> 01:39:54,537
I still know which stars are ours.

1159
01:40:05,183 --> 01:40:06,514
Well,

1160
01:40:08,252 --> 01:40:11,050
call me.
Call me if you ever get to Los Angeles.

1161
01:40:11,923 --> 01:40:15,757
Yeah, sure.
If you ever find yourself in Shelburne Falls...

1162
01:40:22,533 --> 01:40:23,557
Oh.

1163
01:40:23,634 --> 01:40:24,623
Oh.

1164
01:40:39,350 --> 01:40:43,548
You offered to rescue me
from my own wedding.

1165
01:40:45,923 --> 01:40:47,618
You remember that?

1166
01:40:49,260 --> 01:40:50,488
Yeah.

1167
01:40:57,134 --> 01:40:59,932
Not entirely sure what I wanted that day.

1168
01:41:01,939 --> 01:41:04,499
Not sure what I should have wanted.

1169
01:41:05,543 --> 01:41:09,479
But I have thought about you, singing.

1170
01:41:09,547 --> 01:41:11,708
I wish I could sing for you again.

1171
01:41:16,120 --> 01:41:20,454
You can't know how much it mattered.

1172
01:41:22,159 --> 01:41:26,858
But don't you think at least one of us
should have married Harris.

1173
01:41:30,468 --> 01:41:31,833
I think

1174
01:41:33,371 --> 01:41:35,532
we did what we needed to do.

1175
01:41:44,081 --> 01:41:45,241
Yeah.

1176
01:41:47,818 --> 01:41:49,479
I suppose we did.

1177
01:42:54,452 --> 01:42:55,578
Can I ask you a question?

1178
01:42:56,387 --> 01:42:57,718
Of course.

1179
01:42:59,390 --> 01:43:00,880
Who's Harris?

1180
01:43:04,161 --> 01:43:07,096
Harris was a boy that your mother dated

1181
01:43:10,668 --> 01:43:12,260
a long, long time ago.

1182
01:43:13,604 --> 01:43:15,629
Was she in love with him?

1183
01:43:16,173 --> 01:43:18,573
We were all in love with Harris.

1184
01:43:20,644 --> 01:43:22,475
What happened to him?

1185
01:43:24,315 --> 01:43:30,515
He worked with the poor, got married,
had children, became an old man.

1186
01:43:32,089 --> 01:43:35,820
I have to ask. I'm sorry, but I have to know.

1187
01:43:37,261 --> 01:43:42,631
Do you think Mom made
some sort of terrible mistake back then?

1188
01:43:44,769 --> 01:43:49,866
Harris was just a boy, dear.
An unusually attractive one, I'll admit.

1189
01:43:52,143 --> 01:43:54,577
But your mother had a whole life.

1190
01:43:55,613 --> 01:43:57,205
She had you.

1191
01:43:58,582 --> 01:43:59,913
For all the good it did her.

1192
01:44:01,585 --> 01:44:03,746
She sang at my wedding.

1193
01:44:05,589 --> 01:44:07,420
She raised two girls.

1194
01:44:09,326 --> 01:44:13,422
We can't know everything she did.

1195
01:44:16,333 --> 01:44:21,202
But, I can assure you, it was a great deal.

1196
01:44:25,476 --> 01:44:27,569
Guess my cab is here.

1197
01:44:28,712 --> 01:44:31,340
Sorry. She's just been saying strange things.

1198
01:44:31,515 --> 01:44:32,504
Mmm.

1199
01:44:33,884 --> 01:44:36,546
We're mysterious creatures, aren't we?

1200
01:44:38,823 --> 01:44:43,419
And at the end,
so much of it turns out not to matter.

1201
01:44:46,797 --> 01:44:48,560
You really think so?

1202
01:44:51,035 --> 01:44:52,935
Listen to an old lady.

1203
01:45:11,789 --> 01:45:13,017
Hi, Mom.

1204
01:45:13,090 --> 01:45:15,058
Hello, sweetheart.

1205
01:45:16,627 --> 01:45:18,117
How you feeling?

1206
01:45:18,195 --> 01:45:20,356
I feel wonderful.

1207
01:45:20,598 --> 01:45:22,725
I don't feel sick at all.

1208
01:45:24,335 --> 01:45:25,768
Oh, honey.

1209
01:45:26,871 --> 01:45:29,135
You look a little better, too.

1210
01:45:29,473 --> 01:45:31,737
I am a little better, I think.

1211
01:45:35,613 --> 01:45:40,516
I'm gonna get up. I'm going to make
a big breakfast for everybody.

1212
01:45:40,584 --> 01:45:43,519
I think you're being a little too ambitious.

1213
01:45:50,761 --> 01:45:52,160
Will do you do something for me?

1214
01:45:52,963 --> 01:45:54,191
Anything.

1215
01:45:57,468 --> 01:45:59,493
Will you try to be happy?

1216
01:46:01,138 --> 01:46:03,129
That's a tall order, Mom.

1217
01:46:05,142 --> 01:46:09,135
Will you try not to be scared all the time?

1218
01:46:10,481 --> 01:46:12,039
Hmm.

1219
01:46:13,317 --> 01:46:14,784
Because

1220
01:46:17,521 --> 01:46:20,149
there's no such thing as a mistake.

1221
01:46:22,793 --> 01:46:25,193
You get nervous, but...

1222
01:46:27,898 --> 01:46:29,957
But you sing anyway.

1223
01:46:36,006 --> 01:46:39,305
I'm just going to sleep
for a minute now, okay?

1224
01:46:40,911 --> 01:46:42,208
Okay.

1225
01:46:47,718 --> 01:46:49,276
Mommy, I want you.

1226
01:46:49,353 --> 01:46:51,116
Just a second, Connie.

1227
01:46:51,455 --> 01:46:52,513
I want you now!

1228
01:46:52,590 --> 01:46:53,614
What is it, honey?

1229
01:46:53,691 --> 01:46:56,091
I can't get Barbie into her dress.

1230
01:46:56,160 --> 01:46:57,991
Well, she can wait a minute,
don't you think?

1231
01:46:58,062 --> 01:46:59,620
No, she needs you right now!

1232
01:47:00,764 --> 01:47:03,392
She can't bang on that xylophone thing
when I'm working.

1233
01:47:03,467 --> 01:47:05,628
That is so true.

1234
01:47:06,403 --> 01:47:07,768
Here, all yours.

1235
01:47:07,838 --> 01:47:09,965
I'm making dinner, can you just manage
with Nina for 20 minutes?

1236
01:47:10,040 --> 01:47:11,871
I've got a deadline, okay?

1237
01:47:13,110 --> 01:47:15,340
Barbie's going to be late.

1238
01:47:16,814 --> 01:47:19,715
What is she late for, angel?

1239
01:47:20,484 --> 01:47:24,716
Her party, she's going to be late,
she's going to miss everything.

1240
01:47:29,093 --> 01:47:32,859
<i>I see the moon and the moon sees me</i>

1241
01:47:33,631 --> 01:47:37,727
<i>And the moon sees somebody
I'd want to see</i>

1242
01:47:39,169 --> 01:47:43,105
<i>God bless the moon, and God bless me</i>

1243
01:47:43,974 --> 01:47:47,637
<i>And God bless the somebody</i>

1244
01:47:47,711 --> 01:47:49,702
<i>I'd want to see</i>

1245
01:47:51,448 --> 01:47:55,111
<i>God looked down from up above</i>

1246
01:47:55,185 --> 01:47:59,087
<i>And he picked you out for me to love</i>

1247
01:47:59,923 --> 01:48:03,689
<i>He picked you out from all the rest</i>

1248
01:48:04,328 --> 01:48:08,958
<i>'Cause he knew that I loved you
the very best</i>

1249
01:48:10,634 --> 01:48:14,035
<i>I see the moon and the moon sees me</i>

1250
01:48:14,104 --> 01:48:18,438
<i>And the moon sees somebody
I'd want to see</i>

1251
01:48:19,977 --> 01:48:24,505
<i>God bless the moon and God bless me</i>

1252
01:48:25,182 --> 01:48:28,583
<i>And God bless the somebody
I'd want to see</i>

1253
01:48:28,652 --> 01:48:30,381
Good morning.
Hey.

1254
01:48:36,193 --> 01:48:37,251
Sit down.

1255
01:48:37,327 --> 01:48:38,760
Thanks.

1256
01:48:50,741 --> 01:48:52,140
Guess what.

1257
01:48:54,478 --> 01:48:55,911
What?

1258
01:48:57,347 --> 01:48:58,837
I'm pregnant.

1259
01:49:02,419 --> 01:49:03,716
You're kidding.

1260
01:49:05,556 --> 01:49:07,046
Never more serious.

1261
01:49:08,258 --> 01:49:09,418
Wow.

1262
01:49:13,230 --> 01:49:14,993
Oh, uh...

1263
01:49:18,068 --> 01:49:19,660
Are you happy?

1264
01:49:23,207 --> 01:49:25,767
Yeah! Are you happy?

1265
01:49:27,711 --> 01:49:29,076
I think so.

1266
01:49:31,014 --> 01:49:33,005
Yeah, I think I am.

1267
01:49:35,486 --> 01:49:37,716
Sit down. Should you sit down?

1268
01:49:37,788 --> 01:49:40,313
I'm only two months along, I'm fine.

1269
01:49:41,458 --> 01:49:42,823
Oh, my God.

1270
01:49:45,362 --> 01:49:48,729
A baby. We're going to have a baby.

1271
01:49:48,799 --> 01:49:51,097
Which, frankly, scares the hell out of me.

1272
01:49:51,468 --> 01:49:53,026
It'll be great.

1273
01:49:53,604 --> 01:49:55,629
Yeah. I'm sure it will, at times.

1274
01:49:55,706 --> 01:50:00,575
And at times I'm sure I'll be exhausted
and angry

1275
01:50:02,513 --> 01:50:05,277
and think I've made a total mess of my life.

1276
01:50:06,450 --> 01:50:07,974
I'll be there.

1277
01:50:09,186 --> 01:50:10,949
You will, won't you?

1278
01:50:11,889 --> 01:50:17,850
Even if I get confused and strange
and horrible.

1279
01:50:19,296 --> 01:50:22,322
Yeah, I'll do my best.

1280
01:50:24,668 --> 01:50:26,260
I will, too.

1281
01:50:30,974 --> 01:50:35,434
Connie, we're gonna have a baby.

1282
01:50:36,780 --> 01:50:39,044
I know. That's great.

1283
01:50:42,452 --> 01:50:43,646
I'm...

1284
01:50:46,523 --> 01:50:48,548
I'm going to be a father!

1285
01:50:49,126 --> 01:50:51,253
You're going to be an aunt!

1286
01:50:55,732 --> 01:50:57,097
Girls,

1287
01:50:58,468 --> 01:51:00,902
I think you should come upstairs.

1288
01:51:05,876 --> 01:51:07,036
I'll be right here.

1289
01:51:07,110 --> 01:51:08,509
You will, won't you?

1290
01:51:08,579 --> 01:51:09,876
